d) Based on the information provided, we know that both of these proteins are ATP syntheses. They both have the same functionality only in different organisms. Therefore, it would be expected that they should have a fair share of similarity between their sequences. Looking at their alignments, you some similarities between them and the positive score reported for the optimal alignment indicates that the degree of similarity between these sequences is relatively high. Since the gap penalty is set to 8 and a match only rewards 2, having such a high positive score indicates that there is a large amount of matches within the sequences so the degree of similarity must be relatively high.

e) Based on what I have already learned, it is expected that these sequences will align relatively well since they are also both ATP synthases. E.Coli and Humans are not similar as organisms but since these proteins perform the same function, they had relatively high similarity. For this reason, the alignments for the mouse and the bacterium Bacillus subtilis should also have a high degree of similarity between them.

h) The score of the best global alignment is simply the score located in the bottom right of the table. To reduce the amount of space required to complete this score, we should only compute the values along the shortest route from the top left corner to the top right corner. This would be all the values diagonal from the top left until you reach the bottom row. Once you hit the bottom row, if you are not yet at the bottom right corner, simply go right (by adding gaps) until you reach this location. By calculating only this one route, you should be able to calculate the optimal score (in the bottom right corner) while minimizing the amount of space actually being used.
